      "id": "ycja-s82",
      "number": "82",
      "text": "82 (1) Subject to section 12 of the Canada Evidence Act, if a young person is found guilty of an offence, and a youth justice court directs under paragraph 42(2)(b) that the young person be discharged absolutely, or the youth sentence or any disposition under the Young Offenders Act has ceased to have effect, other than an order under section 51 of this Act or section 20.1 of the Young Offenders Act, the young person is deemed not to have been found guilty or convicted of the offence except that (a) the young person may plead autrefois convict in respect of any subsequent charge relating to the offence; (b) a youth justice court may consider the finding of guilt in considering an application under subsection 64(1); (c) any court or justice may consider the finding of guilt in considering an application for judicial interim release or in considering what sentence to impose for any offence; and (d) the Parole Board of Canada or any provincial parole board may consider the finding of guilt in considering an application for conditional release or for a record suspension. (3) No application form for or relating to employment in the federal public service, a Crown corporation, the Canadian Forces, or a federal work, undertaking or business shall contain any question that requires the applicant to disclose that he or she has been charged with or found guilty of an offence in respect of which he or she has been discharged absolutely or has completed the youth sentence.",
      "part": "Part 4 — Sentencing",
      "division": null,
      "heading": "Effect of absolute discharge or termination of youth sentence"
    },
    {
      "id": "ycja-s83",
      "number": "83",
      "text": "83 (1) The purpose of the youth custody and supervision system is to contribute to the protection of society by (a) carrying out sentences imposed by courts through the safe, fair and humane custody and supervision of young persons; and (b) assisting young persons to be rehabilitated and reintegrated into the community as law-abiding citizens, by providing effective programs to young persons in custody and while under supervision in the community. (2) In addition to the principles set out in section 3, the following principles are to be used: (a) that the least restrictive measures consistent with the protection of the public, of personnel and of young persons be used; (b) that young persons sentenced to custody retain the rights of other young persons, except those necessarily removed or restricted as a consequence of a sentence; (c) that the system facilitate the involvement of families and members of the public; (d) that custody and supervision decisions be made in a forthright, fair and timely manner, and that young persons have access to an effective review procedure; and (e) that placements where young persons are treated as adults not disadvantage them with respect to eligibility for and conditions of release.",
      "part": "Part 5 — Custody and Supervision",
      "division": null,
      "heading": "Purpose"
    },
    {
      "id": "ycja-s84",
      "number": "84",
      "text": "84 Subject to subsection 30(3), paragraphs 76(1)(b) and (c) and sections 89 to 93, a young person who is committed to custody shall be held separate and apart from any adult who is detained or held in custody.",
      "part": "Part 5 — Custody and Supervision",
      "division": null,
      "heading": "Young person to be held apart from adults"
    },
    {
      "id": "ycja-s85",
      "number": "85",
      "text": "85 (1) In the youth custody and supervision system in each province there must be at least two levels of custody for young persons distinguished by the degree of restraint. (2) Every youth custody facility that contains one or more levels of custody shall be designated by the lieutenant governor in council or his or her delegate. (3) The provincial director shall, when a young person is committed to custody under paragraph 42(2)(n), (o), (q) or (r) or a specified order, determine the level of custody appropriate for the young person, after having taken into account the factors set out in subsection (5). (5) The factors are (a) that the appropriate level of custody is the least restrictive, having regard to the seriousness of the offence, the needs and circumstances of the young person, the safety of other young persons, and the interests of society; (b) that the level should allow for the best possible match of programs to the young person's needs and behaviour; and (c) the likelihood of escape.",
      "part": "Part 5 — Custody and Supervision",
      "division": null,
      "heading": "Levels of custody"
    },
    {
      "id": "ycja-s86",
      "number": "86",
      "text": "86 (1) The lieutenant governor in council of a province shall ensure that procedures are in place to ensure that the due process rights of the young person are protected with respect to a determination made under subsection 85(3) or (4).",
      "part": "Part 5 — Custody and Supervision",
      "division": null,
      "heading": "Procedural safeguards"
    },
    {
      "id": "ycja-s87",
      "number": "87",
      "text": "87 (1) A young person may apply for a review of a determination that would place the young person in a facility at a level of custody with more than a minimal degree of restraint or transfer to a higher level. (2) The lieutenant governor in council shall ensure that an independent review board conducts the review, with disclosure of relevant information and an opportunity to be heard. (5) A decision of the review board under this section is final.",
      "part": "Part 5 — Custody and Supervision",
      "division": null,
      "heading": "Review"
    },
    {
      "id": "ycja-s88",
      "number": "88",
      "text": "88 The lieutenant governor in council of a province may order that the power to make determinations of the level of custody and to review them be exercised in accordance with the Young Offenders Act, and specified provisions of that Act apply.",
      "part": "Part 5 — Custody and Supervision",
      "division": null,
      "heading": "Functions to be exercised by youth justice court"
    },
    {
      "id": "ycja-s89",
      "number": "89",
      "text": "89 (1) When a young person is twenty years old or older at the time the youth sentence is imposed under paragraph 42(2)(n), (o), (q) or (r), the young person shall be committed to a provincial correctional facility for adults to serve the youth sentence.",
      "part": "Part 5 — Custody and Supervision",
      "division": null,
      "heading": "Exception if young person is twenty years old or older"
    },
    {
      "id": "ycja-s90",
      "number": "90",
      "text": "90 (1) When a youth sentence is imposed committing a young person to custody, the provincial director shall, without delay, designate a youth worker to work with the young person to plan for his or her reintegration into the community. (2) When a portion of a youth sentence is served in the community, the youth worker shall supervise the young person, provide support, and assist in the implementation of the reintegration plan.",
      "part": "Part 5 — Custody and Supervision",
      "division": null,
      "heading": "Youth worker"
    },
    {
      "id": "ycja-s91",
      "number": "91",
      "text": "91 (1) The provincial director may, subject to terms and conditions, authorize a reintegration leave from the youth custody facility for a period not exceeding thirty days for medical, compassionate or humanitarian reasons or for rehabilitation or reintegration, or authorize release on specified days and hours for school, employment, a program or treatment. (4) If the provincial director revokes an authorization or if a young person fails to comply, the young person may be arrested without warrant and returned to custody.",
      "part": "Part 5 — Custody and Supervision",
      "division": null,
      "heading": "Reintegration leave"
    },
    {
      "id": "ycja-s92",
      "number": "92",
      "text": "92 (1) When a young person is committed to custody under paragraph 42(2)(n), (o), (q) or (r), the youth justice court may, on application of the provincial director made after the young person attains the age of eighteen years, authorize the provincial director to direct that the young person serve the remainder of the youth sentence in a provincial correctional facility for adults, if the court considers it in the best interests of the young person or in the public interest.",
      "part": "Part 5 — Custody and Supervision",
      "division": null,
      "heading": "Transfer to adult facility"
    },
    {
      "id": "ycja-s93",
      "number": "93",
      "text": "93 (1) When a young person committed to custody under paragraph 42(2)(n), (o), (q) or (r) is in a youth custody facility when the young person attains the age of twenty years, the young person shall be transferred to a provincial correctional facility for adults to serve the remainder of the youth sentence, unless the provincial director orders that the young person continue to serve it in a youth custody facility.",
      "part": "Part 5 — Custody and Supervision",
      "division": null,
      "heading": "When young person reaches twenty years of age"
    },
    {
      "id": "ycja-s94",
      "number": "94",
      "text": "94 (1) When a young person is committed to custody under paragraph 42(2)(n), (o), (q) or (r) for a period exceeding one year, the provincial director shall cause the young person to be brought before the youth justice court without delay at the end of one year — and at the end of every subsequent year — and the youth justice court shall review the youth sentence. (3) Optional reviews are available on specified timelines on the grounds set out in subsection (6). (6) A youth sentence may be reviewed on the ground that the young person has made sufficient progress to justify a change; the circumstances that led to the youth sentence have changed materially; new services or programs are available; the opportunities for rehabilitation are now greater in the community; or any other ground the court considers appropriate. (19) When a youth justice court reviews a youth sentence, it may confirm the youth sentence; release the young person from custody and place the young person under conditional supervision in accordance with section 105 for a period not exceeding the remainder of the youth sentence; or, on the provincial director's recommendation, convert a paragraph 42(2)(r) sentence to a (q), (n) or (o) sentence as applicable.",
      "part": "Part 5 — Custody and Supervision",
      "division": null,
      "heading": "Annual review"
    },
    {
      "id": "ycja-s95",
      "number": "95",
      "text": "95 Orders under subsections 97(2) and 98(3), paragraph 103(2)(b), subsections 104(1) and 105(1) and paragraph 109(2)(b) are deemed to be youth sentences for the purposes of section 94.",
      "part": "Part 5 — Custody and Supervision",
      "division": null,
      "heading": "Orders are youth sentences"
    },
    {
      "id": "ycja-s96",
      "number": "96",
      "text": "96 (1) When a young person is held in custody under paragraph 42(2)(n), (o), (q) or (r), the provincial director may, if satisfied that the needs of the young person and the interests of society would be better served, recommend to the youth justice court that the young person be released from custody and placed under conditional supervision.",
      "part": "Part 5 — Custody and Supervision",
      "division": null,
      "heading": "Recommendation of provincial director for conditional supervision"
    },
    {
      "id": "ycja-s97",
      "number": "97",
      "text": "97 (1) Every youth sentence imposed under paragraph 42(2)(n) shall contain the following conditions, that the young person, while serving the portion of the youth sentence under supervision in the community, (a) keep the peace and be of good behaviour; (b) report to the provincial director and then be under the supervision of the provincial director; (c) inform the provincial director immediately on being arrested or questioned by the police; (d) report to the police, or any named individual, as instructed by the provincial director; (e) advise the provincial director of the young person's address of residence and report immediately any change in address, occupation, or family or financial situation; and (f) not own, possess or have the control of any weapon, ammunition, prohibited ammunition, prohibited device or explosive substance, except as authorized in writing by the provincial director. (2) The provincial director may set additional conditions that support and address the needs of the young person, promote reintegration and offer adequate protection to the public.",
      "part": "Part 5 — Custody and Supervision",
      "division": null,
      "heading": "Conditions to be included in custody and supervision order"
    },
    {
      "id": "ycja-s98",
      "number": "98",
      "text": "98 (1) Within a reasonable time before the expiry of the custodial portion of a young person's youth sentence, the Attorney General or the provincial director may apply to the youth justice court for an order that the young person remain in custody for a period not exceeding the remainder of the youth sentence. (3) The youth justice court may order that a young person remain in custody for a period not exceeding the remainder of the youth sentence, if it is satisfied that there are reasonable grounds to believe that (a) the young person is likely to commit a serious violent offence before the expiry of the youth sentence; and (b) the conditions that would be imposed if the young person were to serve a portion in the community would not be adequate to prevent the commission of the offence.",
      "part": "Part 5 — Custody and Supervision",
      "division": null,
      "heading": "Application for continuation of custody"
    },
    {
      "id": "ycja-s99",
      "number": "99",
      "text": "99 (1) For the purpose of determining an application under section 98, the youth justice court shall require the provincial director to prepare and submit a report setting out information with respect to the factors set out in subsection 98(4).",
      "part": "Part 5 — Custody and Supervision",
      "division": null,
      "heading": "Report"
    },
    {
      "id": "ycja-s100",
      "number": "100",
      "text": "100 When a youth justice court makes an order under subsection 98(3), it shall state its reasons in the record and provide a copy of the order and, on request, the reasons to the young person, the counsel and a parent, the Attorney General and the provincial director.",
      "part": "Part 5 — Custody and Supervision",
      "division": null,
      "heading": "Reasons"
    },
    {
      "id": "ycja-s101",
      "number": "101",
      "text": "101 (1) An order made under subsection 98(3), or the refusal to make such an order, shall, on application made within thirty days, be reviewed by the court of appeal, which may confirm or reverse the decision.",
      "part": "Part 5 — Custody and Supervision",
      "division": null,
      "heading": "Review of youth justice court decision"
    },
    {
      "id": "ycja-s102",
      "number": "102",
      "text": "102 (1) If the provincial director has reasonable grounds to believe that a young person has breached or is about to breach a condition under section 97, the provincial director may, in writing, (a) permit the young person to continue to serve a portion of the youth sentence in the community, on the same or different conditions; or (b) if satisfied that the breach is a serious one that increases the risk to public safety, order that the young person be remanded to a youth custody facility until a review is conducted.",
      "part": "Part 5 — Custody and Supervision",
      "division": null,
      "heading": "Breach of conditions"
    },
    {
      "id": "ycja-s103",
      "number": "103",
      "text": "103 (1) When the case of a young person is referred to the youth justice court under section 108, the provincial director shall cause the young person to be brought before the court, which shall, after giving the young person an opportunity to be heard, decide whether the young person breached or was about to breach a condition and make an order under subsection (2). (2) On completion of the review, the court shall order that the young person continue to serve the remainder in the community (varying or imposing conditions) or, if satisfied the breach was serious, order that the young person remain in custody for a period not exceeding the remainder.",
      "part": "Part 5 — Custody and Supervision",
      "division": null,
      "heading": "Review by youth justice court"
    },
    {
      "id": "ycja-s104",
      "number": "104",
      "text": "104 (1) When a young person on whom a youth sentence under paragraph 42(2)(o), (q) or (r) has been imposed is held in custody and an application is made by the Attorney General within a reasonable time before expiry of the custodial portion, the youth justice court may, if satisfied that there are reasonable grounds to believe that the young person is likely to commit an offence causing the death of or serious harm to another person before expiry, order that the young person remain in custody for a period not exceeding the remainder of the youth sentence.",
      "part": "Part 5 — Custody and Supervision",
      "division": null,
      "heading": "Continuation of custody"
    },
    {
      "id": "ycja-s105",
      "number": "105",
      "text": "105 (1) The provincial director shall cause a young person on whom a youth sentence under paragraph 42(2)(o), (q) or (r) has been imposed to be brought before the youth justice court at least one month before the expiry of the custodial portion, and the court shall, after giving the young person an opportunity to be heard, by order, set the conditions of the young person's conditional supervision. (2) The order shall include conditions that the young person keep the peace and be of good behaviour, appear before the court when required, report to the provincial director immediately on release, inform the provincial director immediately on being arrested or questioned by police, report as instructed, advise of address and report changes, not possess weapons except as authorized, and comply with any reasonable instructions to prevent a breach or protect society. (3) The court may include additional conditions respecting residence, employment, schooling and reintegration.",
      "part": "Part 5 — Custody and Supervision",
      "division": null,
      "heading": "Conditional supervision"
    },
    {
      "id": "ycja-s106",
      "number": "106",
      "text": "106 If the provincial director has reasonable grounds to believe that a young person has breached or is about to breach a condition of an order made under subsection 105(1), the provincial director may, in writing, (a) suspend the conditional supervision; and (b) order that the young person be remanded to any youth custody facility that the provincial director considers appropriate until a review is conducted.",
      "part": "Part 5 — Custody and Supervision",
      "division": null,
      "heading": "Suspension of conditional supervision"
    },
    {
      "id": "ycja-s107",
      "number": "107",
      "text": "107 (1) If the conditional supervision of a young person is suspended under section 106, the provincial director may issue a warrant in writing authorizing the apprehension of the young person and, until the young person is apprehended, the young person is deemed not to be continuing to serve the youth sentence. (3) If a peace officer believes on reasonable grounds that a warrant issued under subsection (1) is in force in respect of a young person, the peace officer may arrest the young person without the warrant at any place in Canada.",
      "part": "Part 5 — Custody and Supervision",
      "division": null,
      "heading": "Apprehension"
    },
    {
      "id": "ycja-s108",
      "number": "108",
      "text": "108 Without delay after the remand to custody of a young person whose conditional supervision has been suspended under section 106, or after being informed of the arrest, the provincial director shall review the case and, within forty-eight hours, cancel the suspension or refer the case to the youth justice court for a review under section 109.",
      "part": "Part 5 — Custody and Supervision",
      "division": null,
      "heading": "Review by provincial director"
    },
    {
      "id": "ycja-s109",
      "number": "109",
      "text": "109 (1) If the case of a young person is referred to the youth justice court under section 108, the provincial director shall cause the young person to be brought before the court, which shall, after giving the young person an opportunity to be heard, decide whether the young person breached or was about to breach a condition and make an order under subsection (2). (2) On completion of the review, the court shall order the cancellation of the suspension (varying or imposing conditions), the continuation of the suspension for a period not exceeding the remainder of the youth sentence (with the young person remaining in custody), or, in the case of a deferred custody and supervision order, that the young person serve the remainder as if it were a custody and supervision order under paragraph 42(2)(n).",
      "part": "Part 5 — Custody and Supervision",
      "division": null,
      "heading": "Review by youth justice court"
    },
    {
      "id": "ycja-s110",
      "number": "110",
      "text": "110 (1) Subject to this section, no person shall publish the name of a young person, or any other information related to a young person, if it would identify the young person as a young person dealt with under this Act. (2) Subsection (1) does not apply (a) in a case where the information relates to a young person who has received an adult sentence; or (c) in a case where the publication of information is made in the course of the administration of justice, if it is not the purpose of the publication to make the information known in the community. (3) A young person referred to in subsection (1) may, after he or she attains the age of eighteen years, publish or cause to be published information that would identify him or her as having been dealt with under this Act or the Young Offenders Act, provided that he or she is not in custody pursuant to either Act at the time of the publication. (4) A youth justice court judge shall, on the ex parte application of a peace officer, make an order permitting any person to publish information that identifies a young person as having committed or allegedly committed an indictable offence, if the judge is satisfied that (a) there is reason to believe that the young person is a danger to others; and (b) publication of the information is necessary to assist in apprehending the young person. (5) An order made under subsection (4) ceases to have effect five days after it is made. (6) The youth justice court may, on the application of a young person referred to in subsection (1), make an order permitting the young person to publish information that would identify him or her as having been dealt with under this Act or the Young Offenders Act, if the court is satisfied that the publication would not be contrary to the young person's best interests or the public interest.",
      "part": "Part 6 — Publication, Records and Information",
      "division": null,
      "heading": "Identity of offender not to be published"
    },
    {
      "id": "ycja-s111",
      "number": "111",
      "text": "111 (1) Subject to this section, no person shall publish the name of a child or young person, or any other information related to a child or a young person, if it would identify the child or young person as having been a victim of, or as having appeared as a witness in connection with, an offence committed or alleged to have been committed by a young person. (2) Information that would serve to identify a child or young person referred to in subsection (1) as having been a victim or a witness may be published by that child or young person after he or she attains the age of eighteen years or before that age with the consent of his or her parents, or by the parents if the child or young person is deceased. (3) The youth justice court may, on the application of a child or a young person referred to in subsection (1), make an order permitting the child or young person to publish information that would identify him or her as having been a victim or a witness if the court is satisfied that the publication would not be contrary to his or her best interests or the public interest.",
      "part": "Part 6 — Publication, Records and Information",
      "division": null,
      "heading": "Identity of victim or witness not to be published"
    },
    {
      "id": "ycja-s112",
      "number": "112",
      "text": "112 Once information is published under subsection 110(3) or (6) or 111(2) or (3), subsection 110(1) or 111(1), as the case may be, no longer applies in respect of the information.",
