    {
      "id": "ycja-s113",
      "number": "113",
      "text": "113 (1) The Identification of Criminals Act applies in respect of young persons. (2) No fingerprint, palmprint or photograph or other measurement, process or operation referred to in the Identification of Criminals Act shall be taken of, or applied in respect of, a young person who is charged with having committed an offence except in the circumstances in which an adult may, under that Act, be subjected to the measurements, processes and operations.",
      "part": "Part 6 — Publication, Records and Information",
      "division": null,
      "heading": "Identification of Criminals Act applies"
    },
    {
      "id": "ycja-s114",
      "number": "114",
      "text": "114 A youth justice court, review board or any court dealing with matters arising out of proceedings under this Act may keep a record of any case that comes before it arising under this Act.",
      "part": "Part 6 — Publication, Records and Information",
      "division": null,
      "heading": "Youth justice court, review board and other courts"
    },
    {
      "id": "ycja-s115",
      "number": "115",
      "text": "115 (1) A record relating to any offence alleged to have been committed by a young person, including the original or a copy of any fingerprints or photographs of the young person, may be kept by any police force responsible for or participating in the investigation of the offence. (1.1) The police force shall keep a record of any extrajudicial measures that they use to deal with young persons. (2) When a young person is charged with having committed an offence in respect of which an adult may be subjected to any measurement, process or operation referred to in the Identification of Criminals Act, the police force responsible for the investigation may provide a record relating to the offence to the Royal Canadian Mounted Police. If the young person is found guilty of the offence, the police force shall provide the record. (3) The Royal Canadian Mounted Police shall keep the records provided under subsection (2) in the central repository that the Commissioner may designate for the purpose of keeping criminal history files or records of offenders.",
      "part": "Part 6 — Publication, Records and Information",
      "division": null,
      "heading": "Police records"
    },
    {
      "id": "ycja-s116",
      "number": "116",
      "text": "116 (1) A department or an agency of any government in Canada may keep records containing information obtained by the department or agency for the purposes of an investigation of an offence alleged to have been committed by a young person; for use in proceedings against a young person under this Act; for the purpose of administering a youth sentence or an order; for the purpose of considering whether to use extrajudicial measures; or as a result of the use of extrajudicial measures.",
      "part": "Part 6 — Publication, Records and Information",
      "division": null,
      "heading": "Government records"
    },
    {
      "id": "ycja-s117",
      "number": "117",
      "text": "117 Sections 118 to 129 do not apply to records kept in respect of an offence for which an adult sentence has been imposed once the time allowed for appeal has expired or, if an appeal is taken, all proceedings have been completed and the appeal court has upheld an adult sentence. The record shall be dealt with as a record of an adult.",
      "part": "Part 6 — Publication, Records and Information",
      "division": null,
      "heading": "Exception — adult sentence"
    },
    {
      "id": "ycja-s118",
      "number": "118",
      "text": "118 (1) Except as authorized or required by this Act, no person shall be given access to a record kept under sections 114 to 116, and no information contained in it may be given to any person, where to do so would identify the young person to whom it relates as a young person dealt with under this Act. (2) No person who is employed in keeping or maintaining records referred to in subsection (1) is restricted from doing anything prohibited under subsection (1) with respect to any other person so employed.",
      "part": "Part 6 — Publication, Records and Information",
      "division": null,
      "heading": "No access unless authorized"
    },
    {
      "id": "ycja-s119",
      "number": "119",
      "text": "119 (1) Subject to subsections (4) to (6), from the date that a record is created until the end of the applicable period set out in subsection (2), the following persons, on request, shall be given access to a record kept under section 114, and may be given access to a record kept under sections 115 and 116: the young person to whom the record relates; the young person's counsel; the Attorney General; the victim of the offence or alleged offence; the parents of the young person during proceedings or the term of a youth sentence; any adult assisting the young person under subsection 25(7); any peace officer for law enforcement purposes or the administration of the case; a judge, court or review board for proceedings against the young person; the provincial director or the director of the facility where the young person is serving a sentence; a person participating in a conference or the administration of extrajudicial measures; an ombudsman, privacy or information commissioner; a coroner or child advocate; a person acting under the Firearms Act; specified government members exercising duties under this Act or supervising the young person; a person carrying out a criminal record check required for employment; an employee for statistics under the Statistics Act; an employee administering the Canadian Passport Order; an accused or counsel who swears an affidavit that access is necessary to make full answer and defence; a designated person; and any person a youth justice court judge considers has a valid interest, for research/statistics or the proper administration of justice. (2) The period of access is (a) if an extrajudicial sanction is used, two years after the young person consents to the sanction; (b) if the young person is acquitted otherwise than by reason of a verdict of not criminally responsible on account of mental disorder, two months after the time for appeal or three months after appeal proceedings are completed; (c) if the charge is dismissed (other than by acquittal), withdrawn, or the young person is found guilty and a reprimand is given, two months after; (d) if the charge is stayed with no proceedings for one year, at the end of that year; (e) if the youth sentence is an absolute discharge, one year after the finding of guilt; (f) if the youth sentence is a conditional discharge, three years after the finding of guilt; (g) if a summary conviction offence, three years after the youth sentence has been completed; (h) if an indictable offence, five years after the youth sentence has been completed; and (i) and (j) extended periods where the young person is found guilty of a further offence during the access period. (9) If, during the period of access, the young person is convicted of an offence committed when he or she is an adult, section 82 no longer applies, the record is dealt with as an adult record, and the finding of guilt is deemed to be a conviction for the purposes of the Criminal Records Act.",
      "part": "Part 6 — Publication, Records and Information",
      "division": null,
      "heading": "Persons having access to records"
    },
    {
      "id": "ycja-s120",
      "number": "120",
      "text": "120 (1) Specified persons may, during the period set out in subsection (3), be given access to a record kept under subsection 115(3) in respect of an offence set out in the schedule, including the young person, counsel, an employee for statistics, a person with a valid research interest, and the Attorney General or a peace officer for investigating further schedule offences or establishing the existence of an order, and any person for the purposes of the Firearms Act. (3) The period of access is (a) if the offence is an indictable offence (other than a serious violent offence for which adult-sentence notice was given), the period starting at the end of the applicable period in paragraphs 119(2)(h) to (j) and ending five years later; and (b) if the offence is a serious violent offence for which the Attorney General has given notice under subsection 64(2), the period starting at the end of the applicable period and continuing indefinitely.",
      "part": "Part 6 — Publication, Records and Information",
      "division": null,
      "heading": "Access to R.C.M.P. records"
    },
    {
      "id": "ycja-s122",
      "number": "122",
      "text": "122 A person who is required or authorized to be given access to a record under section 119, 120, 123 or 124 may be given any information contained in the record and may be given a copy of any part of the record.",
      "part": "Part 6 — Publication, Records and Information",
      "division": null,
      "heading": "Disclosure of information and copies of record"
    },
    {
      "id": "ycja-s123",
      "number": "123",
      "text": "123 (1) A youth justice court judge may, on application by a person after the end of the applicable period set out in subsection 119(2), order that the person be given access to all or part of a record kept under sections 114 to 116, if satisfied that the person has a valid and substantial interest, access is necessary in the interest of the proper administration of justice, and disclosure is not prohibited under any other Act; or that access is desirable in the public interest for research or statistical purposes.",
      "part": "Part 6 — Publication, Records and Information",
      "division": null,
      "heading": "Where records may be made available"
    },
    {
      "id": "ycja-s124",
      "number": "124",
      "text": "124 A young person to whom a record relates and his or her counsel may have access to the record at any time.",
      "part": "Part 6 — Publication, Records and Information",
      "division": null,
      "heading": "Access to record by young person"
    },
    {
      "id": "ycja-s125",
      "number": "125",
      "text": "125 (1) A peace officer may disclose to any person any information in a record kept under section 114 or 115 that it is necessary to disclose in the conduct of the investigation of an offence. (6) The provincial director, a youth worker, the Attorney General, a peace officer or any other person engaged in the provision of services to young persons may disclose to any professional or other person engaged in the supervision or care of a young person — including a representative of any school board or school or any other educational or training institution — any information contained in a record kept under sections 114 to 116 if the disclosure is necessary (a) to ensure compliance by the young person with an authorization under section 91 or an order of the youth justice court; (b) to ensure the safety of staff, students or other persons; or (c) to facilitate the rehabilitation of the young person. (7) A person to whom information is disclosed under subsection (6) shall keep the information separate from any other record of the young person, ensure no other person has access except as authorized, and destroy their copy when it is no longer required. (8) No information may be disclosed under this section after the end of the applicable period set out in subsection 119(2).",
      "part": "Part 6 — Publication, Records and Information",
      "division": null,
      "heading": "Disclosure by peace officer during investigation"
    },
    {
      "id": "ycja-s126",
      "number": "126",
      "text": "126 When records originally kept under sections 114 to 116 are under the custody or control of the Librarian and Archivist of Canada or the archivist for any province, that person may disclose any information contained in the records to any other person if a youth justice court judge is satisfied that the disclosure is desirable in the public interest for research or statistical purposes and the person undertakes not to disclose it in identifying form.",
      "part": "Part 6 — Publication, Records and Information",
      "division": null,
      "heading": "Records in the custody of archivists"
    },
    {
      "id": "ycja-s127",
      "number": "127",
      "text": "127 (1) The youth justice court may, on the application of the provincial director, the Attorney General or a peace officer, make an order permitting the applicant to disclose to specified persons information about a young person, if the court is satisfied that the disclosure is necessary, having regard to (a) the young person has been found guilty of an offence involving serious personal injury; (b) the young person poses a risk of serious harm to persons; and (c) the disclosure of the information is relevant to the avoidance of that risk. (4) No information may be disclosed under subsection (1) after the end of the applicable period set out in subsection 119(2).",
      "part": "Part 6 — Publication, Records and Information",
      "division": null,
      "heading": "Disclosure with court order"
    },
    {
      "id": "ycja-s128",
      "number": "128",
      "text": "128 (1) Subject to sections 123, 124 and 126, after the end of the applicable period set out in section 119 or 120 no record kept under sections 114 to 116 may be used for any purpose that would identify the young person to whom the record relates as a young person dealt with under this Act or the Young Offenders Act. (2) Subject to paragraph 125(7)(c), any record kept under sections 114 to 116, other than a record kept under subsection 115(3), may, in the discretion of the person or body keeping the record, be destroyed or transmitted to the Librarian and Archivist of Canada or the archivist for any province, at any time before or after the end of the applicable period. (3) All records kept under subsection 115(3) shall be destroyed or, if the Librarian and Archivist of Canada requires it, transmitted to the Librarian and Archivist, at the end of the applicable period set out in section 119 or 120. (4) The Commissioner of the Royal Canadian Mounted Police shall remove a record from the automated criminal conviction records retrieval system at the end of the applicable period referred to in section 119; however, information relating to a prohibition order shall be removed only at the end of the period for which the order is in force.",
      "part": "Part 6 — Publication, Records and Information",
      "division": null,
      "heading": "Effect of end of access periods"
    },
    {
      "id": "ycja-s129",
      "number": "129",
      "text": "129 No person who is given access to a record or to whom information is disclosed under this Act shall disclose that information to any other person unless the disclosure is authorized under this Act.",
      "part": "Part 6 — Publication, Records and Information",
      "division": null,
      "heading": "No subsequent disclosure"
    },
    {
      "id": "ycja-s130",
      "number": "130",
      "text": "130 (1) Subject to subsection (2), a youth justice court judge who, prior to an adjudication in respect of a young person charged with an offence, examines a pre-sentence report or has, after a guilty plea or finding of guilt, heard submissions as to sentence and then there has been a change of plea, shall not conduct or continue the trial of the young person for the offence and shall transfer the case to another judge. (2) A youth justice court judge may, with the consent of the young person and the prosecutor, conduct or continue the trial if satisfied that he or she has not been predisposed.",
      "part": "Part 7 — General Provisions",
      "division": null,
      "heading": "Disqualification of judge"
    },
    {
      "id": "ycja-s131",
      "number": "131",
      "text": "131 (1) A youth justice court judge who acts in the place of another under subsection 669.2(1) of the Criminal Code shall, if an adjudication has been made, proceed to sentence or make the appropriate order, or, if no adjudication has been made, recommence the trial as if no evidence had been taken.",
      "part": "Part 7 — General Provisions",
      "division": null,
      "heading": "Powers of substitute youth justice court judge"
    },
    {
      "id": "ycja-s132",
      "number": "132",
      "text": "132 (1) Subject to subsection (2), a court or justice before whom proceedings are carried out under this Act may exclude any person from all or part of the proceedings if the court considers the person's presence unnecessary and is of the opinion that (a) any evidence or information would be seriously injurious or prejudicial to the young person, a child or young person witness, or a child or young person victim; or (b) it would be in the interest of public morals, the maintenance of order or the proper administration of justice to exclude any or all members of the public. (2) A court may not exclude the prosecutor, the young person and their counsel or parent or adult assistant, the provincial director or agent, or the assigned youth worker (subject to specified exceptions).",
      "part": "Part 7 — General Provisions",
      "division": null,
      "heading": "Exclusion from hearing"
    },
    {
      "id": "ycja-s133",
      "number": "133",
      "text": "133 Despite subsections 478(1) and (3) of the Criminal Code, a young person charged with an offence alleged to have been committed in one province may, if the Attorney General of the province consents, appear before a youth justice court of any other province, and if the young person pleads guilty and the court is satisfied the facts support the charge, the court shall find the young person guilty.",
      "part": "Part 7 — General Provisions",
      "division": null,
      "heading": "Transfer of charges"
    },
    {
      "id": "ycja-s134",
      "number": "134",
      "text": "134 Applications for the forfeiture of amounts set out in undertakings, release orders or recognizances binding young persons shall be made to the youth justice court.",
      "part": "Part 7 — General Provisions",
      "division": null,
      "heading": "Applications for forfeiture"
    },
    {
      "id": "ycja-s135",
      "number": "135",
      "text": "135 (1) If an undertaking, release order or recognizance binding a young person has been endorsed with a certificate under subsection 770(1) of the Criminal Code, a youth justice court judge shall, on the request of the Attorney General, fix a time and place for the hearing of an application for forfeiture and cause notice to be given to each principal and surety. (2) The youth justice court judge may, after giving the parties an opportunity to be heard, grant or refuse the application and make any order with respect to forfeiture that the judge considers proper.",
      "part": "Part 7 — General Provisions",
      "division": null,
      "heading": "Proceedings in case of default"
    },
    {
      "id": "ycja-s136",
      "number": "136",
      "text": "136 (1) Every person who (a) induces or assists a young person to leave unlawfully a place of custody or other place in which the young person has been placed in accordance with a youth sentence or a disposition imposed under the Young Offenders Act, (b) unlawfully removes a young person from a place referred to in paragraph (a), (c) knowingly harbours or conceals a young person who has unlawfully left a place referred to in paragraph (a), (d) wilfully induces or assists a young person to breach or disobey a term or condition of a youth sentence or other order of the youth justice court, or a term or condition of a disposition or other order under the Young Offenders Act, or (e) wilfully prevents or interferes with the performance by a young person of a term or condition of a youth sentence or other order of the youth justice court, or a term or condition of a disposition or other order under the Young Offenders Act, is guilty of an indictable offence and liable to imprisonment for a term not exceeding two years or is guilty of an offence punishable on summary conviction. (2) The jurisdiction of a provincial court judge to try an adult charged with an indictable offence under this section is absolute and does not depend on the consent of the accused.",
      "part": "Part 7 — General Provisions",
      "division": null,
      "heading": "Inducing a young person, etc."
    },
    {
      "id": "ycja-s137",
      "number": "137",
      "text": "137 Every person who is subject to a youth sentence imposed under any of paragraphs 42(2)(c) to (m) or (s) of this Act, to a victim fine surcharge ordered under subsection 53(2) of this Act or to a disposition made under any of paragraphs 20(1)(a.1) to (g), (j) or (l) of the Young Offenders Act, and who wilfully fails or refuses to comply with that sentence, surcharge or disposition is guilty of an offence punishable on summary conviction.",
      "part": "Part 7 — General Provisions",
      "division": null,
      "heading": "Failure to comply with sentence or disposition"
    },
    {
      "id": "ycja-s138",
      "number": "138",
      "text": "138 (1) Every person who contravenes subsection 110(1) (identity of offender not to be published), 111(1) (identity of victim or witness not to be published), 118(1) (no access to records unless authorized) or 128(3) (disposal of R.C.M.P. records) or section 129 (no subsequent disclosure) of this Act, or subsection 38(1), (1.12), (1.14) or (1.15), 45(2) or 46(1) of the Young Offenders Act, (a) is guilty of an indictable offence and liable to imprisonment for a term not exceeding two years; or (b) is guilty of an offence punishable on summary conviction. (2) The jurisdiction of a provincial court judge to try an adult charged with an offence under paragraph (1)(a) is absolute and does not depend on the consent of the accused.",
      "part": "Part 7 — General Provisions",
      "division": null,
      "heading": "Offences — publication and records"
    },
    {
      "id": "ycja-s139",
      "number": "139",
      "text": "139 (1) Every person who wilfully fails to comply with section 30 (designated place of temporary detention), or with an undertaking entered into under subsection 31(3) (condition of placement), (a) is guilty of an indictable offence and liable to imprisonment for a term not exceeding two years; or (b) is guilty of an offence punishable on summary conviction. (2) Every person who wilfully fails to comply with section 7 of the Young Offenders Act, or with an undertaking entered into under subsection 7.1(2) of that Act is guilty of an offence punishable on summary conviction. (3) Any person who uses or authorizes the use of an application form in contravention of subsection 82(3) (application for employment) is guilty of an offence punishable on summary conviction.",
      "part": "Part 7 — General Provisions",
      "division": null,
      "heading": "Offence and punishment — detention"
    },
    {
      "id": "ycja-s140",
      "number": "140",
      "text": "140 Except to the extent that it is inconsistent with or excluded by this Act, the provisions of the Criminal Code apply, with any modifications that the circumstances require, in respect of offences alleged to have been committed by young persons.",
      "part": "Part 7 — General Provisions",
      "division": null,
      "heading": "Application of Criminal Code"
    },
    {
      "id": "ycja-s141",
      "number": "141",
      "text": "141 (1) Except to the extent that they are inconsistent with or excluded by this Act, section 16 (defence of mental disorder) and Part XX.1 (mental disorder) of the Criminal Code apply, with any modifications that the circumstances require, in respect of proceedings under this Act in relation to offences alleged to have been committed by young persons. (10) For the purpose of applying subsection 672.33(1) of the Criminal Code to proceedings under this Act, wherever in that subsection a reference is made to two years, there shall be substituted a reference to one year. (11) A reference in Part XX.1 of the Criminal Code to a hospital in a province shall be construed as a reference to a hospital designated by the Minister of Health for the province for the custody, treatment or assessment of young persons.",
      "part": "Part 7 — General Provisions",
      "division": null,
      "heading": "Sections of Criminal Code applicable"
    },
    {
      "id": "ycja-s142",
      "number": "142",
      "text": "142 (1) Subject to this section and except to the extent that they are inconsistent with this Act, the provisions of Part XXVII (summary conviction offences) of the Criminal Code, and any other provisions of that Act that apply in respect of summary conviction offences and relate to trial proceedings, apply to proceedings under this Act in respect of specified recognizance orders and breaches, in respect of a summary conviction offence, and in respect of an indictable offence as if it were defined as a summary conviction offence. (2) For greater certainty and despite subsection (1), an indictable offence committed by a young person is, for the purposes of this Act or any other Act of Parliament, an indictable offence.",
      "part": "Part 7 — General Provisions",
      "division": null,
      "heading": "Part XXVII and summary conviction trial provisions of Criminal Code to apply"
    },
    {
      "id": "ycja-s143",
      "number": "143",
      "text": "143 Indictable offences and offences punishable on summary conviction may under this Act be charged in the same information or indictment and tried jointly.",
      "part": "Part 7 — General Provisions",
      "division": null,
      "heading": "Counts charged in information"
    },
    {
      "id": "ycja-s144",
      "number": "144",
      "text": "144 (1) If a person is required to attend to give evidence before a youth justice court, the subpoena directed to that person may be issued by a youth justice court judge, whether or not the person is within the same province as the youth justice court.",
      "part": "Part 7 — General Provisions",
      "division": null,
      "heading": "Issue of subpoena"
    },
    {
      "id": "ycja-s145",
      "number": "145",
      "text": "145 A warrant issued by a youth justice court may be executed anywhere in Canada.",
      "part": "Part 7 — General Provisions",
      "division": null,
      "heading": "Warrant"
    },
    {
      "id": "ycja-s146",
      "number": "146",
      "text": "146 (1) Subject to this section, the law relating to the admissibility of statements made by persons accused of committing offences applies in respect of young persons. (2) No oral or written statement made by a young person who is less than eighteen years old, to a peace officer or to any other person who is, in law, a person in authority, on the arrest or detention of the young person or in circumstances where the peace officer or other person has reasonable grounds for believing that the young person has committed an offence is admissible against the young person unless (a) the statement was voluntary; (b) the person to whom the statement was made has, before the statement was made, clearly explained to the young person, in language appropriate to his or her age and understanding, that the young person is under no obligation to make a statement, any statement may be used as evidence, the young person has the right to consult counsel and a parent or other person, and any statement is required to be made in the presence of counsel and any other person consulted, unless the young person desires otherwise; (c) the young person has, before the statement was made, been given a reasonable opportunity to consult with counsel and with a parent or, in the absence of a parent, an adult relative or other appropriate adult; and (d) if the young person consults a person, the young person has been given a reasonable opportunity to make the statement in the presence of that person. (4) A young person may waive the rights under paragraph (2)(c) or (d) but any such waiver must be recorded on video tape or audio tape, or be in writing and contain a signed statement that he or she has been informed of the right being waived.",
      "part": "Part 7 — General Provisions",
      "division": null,
      "heading": "General law on admissibility of statements to apply"
    },
    {
      "id": "ycja-s147",
      "number": "147",
      "text": "147 (1) Subject to subsection (2), if a young person is assessed in accordance with an order made under subsection 34(1), no statement made by the young person during the course and for the purposes of the assessment is admissible in evidence, without the consent of the young person, in any proceeding.",
      "part": "Part 7 — General Provisions",
      "division": null,
      "heading": "Statements not admissible against young person"
    },
    {
      "id": "ycja-s148",
      "number": "148",
      "text": "148 (1) In any proceedings under this Act, the testimony of a parent as to the age of a person of whom he or she is a parent is admissible as evidence of the age of that person.",
      "part": "Part 7 — General Provisions",
      "division": null,
      "heading": "Testimony of a parent"
    },
    {
      "id": "ycja-s149",
      "number": "149",
      "text": "149 (1) A party to any proceedings under this Act may admit any relevant fact or matter for the purpose of dispensing with proof of it.",
      "part": "Part 7 — General Provisions",
      "division": null,
      "heading": "Admissions"
    },
    {
      "id": "ycja-s150",
      "number": "150",
      "text": "150 Any evidence material to proceedings under this Act that would not but for this section be admissible in evidence may, with the consent of the parties and if the young person is represented by counsel, be given in such proceedings.",
      "part": "Part 7 — General Provisions",
      "division": null,
      "heading": "Material evidence"
    },
    {
      "id": "ycja-s151",
      "number": "151",
      "text": "151 The evidence of a child or a young person may be taken in proceedings under this Act only after the youth justice court judge or the justice has, if the witness is a child, instructed the child as to the duty to speak the truth and the consequences of failing to do so, and, if the witness is a young person and the judge or justice considers it necessary, so instructed the young person.",
      "part": "Part 7 — General Provisions",
      "division": null,
      "heading": "Evidence of a child or young person"
    },
    {
      "id": "ycja-s152",
      "number": "152",
      "text": "152 (1) For the purposes of this Act, service of any document may be proved by oral evidence given under oath by, or by the affidavit or statutory declaration of, the person claiming to have personally served it or sent it by confirmed delivery service.",
      "part": "Part 7 — General Provisions",
      "division": null,
      "heading": "Proof of service"
    },
    {
      "id": "ycja-s153",
      "number": "153",
      "text": "153 It is not necessary to the validity of any information, indictment, summons, warrant, minute, sentence, conviction, order or other process or document laid, issued, filed or entered in any proceedings under this Act that any seal be attached or affixed to it.",
      "part": "Part 7 — General Provisions",
      "division": null,
      "heading": "Seal not required"
    },
    {
      "id": "ycja-s154",
      "number": "154",
      "text": "154 (1) The forms prescribed under section 155, varied to suit the case, or forms to the like effect, are valid and sufficient in the circumstances for which they are provided.",
      "part": "Part 7 — General Provisions",
      "division": null,
      "heading": "Forms"
    },
    {
      "id": "ycja-s155",
      "number": "155",
      "text": "155 The Governor in Council may make regulations (a) prescribing forms that may be used for the purposes of this Act; (b) establishing uniform rules of court for youth justice courts across Canada, including rules regulating the practice and procedure to be followed by youth justice courts; and (c) generally for carrying out the purposes and provisions of this Act.",
      "part": "Part 7 — General Provisions",
      "division": null,
      "heading": "Regulations"
    },
    {
      "id": "ycja-s156",
      "number": "156",
      "text": "156 Any minister of the Crown may, with the approval of the Governor in Council, enter into an agreement with the government of any province providing for payments by Canada to the province in respect of costs incurred for care of and services provided to young persons dealt with under this Act.",
      "part": "Part 7 — General Provisions",
      "division": null,
      "heading": "Agreements with provinces"
    },
    {
      "id": "ycja-s157",
      "number": "157",
      "text": "157 The Attorney General of Canada or a minister designated by the lieutenant governor in council of a province may establish (a) programs that are an alternative to judicial proceedings, such as victim-offender reconciliation programs, mediation programs and restitution programs; (b) programs that are an alternative to detention before sentencing, such as bail supervision programs; and (c) programs that are an alternative to custody, such as intensive support and supervision programs, and programs to carry out attendance orders.",
      "part": "Part 7 — General Provisions",
      "division": null,
      "heading": "Community-based programs"
    },
    {
      "id": "ycja-s158",
      "number": "158",
      "text": "158 On and after the coming into force of this section, no proceedings may be commenced under the Young Offenders Act in respect of an offence within the meaning of that Act, or under the Juvenile Delinquents Act in respect of a delinquency within the meaning of that Act.",
      "part": "Part 8 — Transitional Provisions",
      "division": null,
      "heading": "Prohibition on proceedings"
    },
    {
      "id": "ycja-s159",
      "number": "159",
      "text": "159 (1) Subject to section 161, where, before the coming into force of this section, proceedings are commenced under the Young Offenders Act in respect of an offence alleged to have been committed by a person who was at the time a young person within the meaning of that Act, the proceedings and all related matters shall be dealt with as if this Act had not come into force.",
      "part": "Part 8 — Transitional Provisions",
      "division": null,
      "heading": "Proceedings commenced under Young Offenders Act"
    },
    {
      "id": "ycja-s161",
      "number": "161",
      "text": "161 (1) A person referred to in section 159 who is found guilty of an offence or delinquency, other than a person convicted of an offence in ordinary court, shall be sentenced under this Act, except that paragraph 42(2)(r) applies in respect of the offence or delinquency only if the young person consents to its application.",
      "part": "Part 8 — Transitional Provisions",
      "division": null,
      "heading": "Applicable sentence"
    },
    {
      "id": "ycja-s162",
      "number": "162",
      "text": "162 For the purposes of sections 158 and 159, proceedings are commenced by the laying of an information or indictment.",
      "part": "Part 8 — Transitional Provisions",
      "division": null,
      "heading": "Commencement of proceedings"
    },
    {
      "id": "ycja-s163",
      "number": "163",
      "text": "163 Sections 114 to 129 apply, with any modifications that the circumstances require, in respect of records relating to the offence of delinquency under the Juvenile Delinquents Act, and in respect of records kept under sections 40 to 43 of the Young Offenders Act.",
      "part": "Part 8 — Transitional Provisions",
      "division": null,
      "heading": "Application to delinquency and other offending behaviour"
    },
    {
      "id": "ycja-s164",
      "number": "164",
      "text": "164 Any agreement made under the Young Offenders Act remains in force until it expires, unless it is amended or a new agreement is made under this Act.",
      "part": "Part 8 — Transitional Provisions",
      "division": null,
      "heading": "Agreements continue in force"
    },
    {
      "id": "ycja-s165",
      "number": "165",
      "text": "165 (1) Any court established or designated as a youth court for the purposes of the Young Offenders Act is deemed, as of the coming into force of this section, to have been established or designated as a youth justice court for the purposes of this Act. (5) Any program of alternative measures authorized for the purposes of the Young Offenders Act is deemed to be a program of extrajudicial sanctions authorized for the purposes of this Act.",
      "part": "Part 8 — Transitional Provisions",
      "division": null,
      "heading": "Designation of youth justice court"
    },
    {
      "id": "ycja-s166",
      "number": "166",
      "text": "166 Sections 166 to 199 make consequential amendments to other Acts and repeal the Young Offenders Act.",
      "part": "Part 9 — Consequential Amendments, Repeal and Coming into Force",
      "division": null,
      "heading": "Consequential amendments, repeal"
    },
    {
      "id": "ycja-s200",
      "number": "200",
      "text": "200 The provisions of this Act come into force on a day or days to be fixed by order of the Governor in Council. [Note: Act in force April 1, 2003, see SI/2002-91.]",
      "part": "Part 9 — Consequential Amendments, Repeal and Coming into Force",
      "division": null,
      "heading": "Coming into force"
    },
    {
